<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Payment Recommendation for Humanitarian Platform</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      font-size: 12pt;
      line-height: 1.5;
      margin: 36pt;
      color: #111111;
    }
    h1, h2, h3 {
      color: #0f3d2e;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 20pt;
      margin-bottom: 8pt;
    }
    h2 {
      font-size: 15pt;
      margin-top: 22pt;
      margin-bottom: 8pt;
      border-bottom: 1px solid #d8e3de;
      padding-bottom: 4pt;
    }
    h3 {
      font-size: 12.5pt;
      margin-top: 16pt;
      margin-bottom: 6pt;
    }
    p {
      margin: 8pt 0;
    }
    ul {
      margin-top: 6pt;
      margin-bottom: 10pt;
    }
    table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      margin-top: 8pt;
      margin-bottom: 14pt;
    }
    th, td {
      border: 1px solid #cfd9d4;
      padding: 8pt;
      vertical-align: top;
      text-align: left;
    }
    th {
      background: #eef5f1;
    }
    .muted {
      color: #4c5b55;
    }
    .highlight {
      background: #f5faf7;
      border: 1px solid #d8e3de;
      padding: 10pt 12pt;
      margin: 12pt 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Payment Recommendation for the Humanitarian Platform</h1>
  <p class="muted">Prepared on April 19, 2026</p>

  <h2>1. Purpose</h2>
  <p>
    This document recommends the most appropriate payment model and payment gateways for a humanitarian
    platform focused on grassroots impact across Africa, with an initial emphasis on projects led from
    Nigeria and Ghana. The recommendation is based on the platform goals: fundraising, donor trust,
    cause-based giving, local accessibility, and future scalability.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Executive Recommendation</h2>
  <div class="highlight">
    <p><strong>Recommended payment model:</strong> Donation payments, not software subscriptions.</p>
    <p><strong>Primary gateway recommendation:</strong> Flutterwave.</p>
    <p><strong>Secondary optional gateway:</strong> PayPal for international donor trust and recurring support.</p>
    <p><strong>Alternative primary option:</strong> Paystack, especially if the operating entity is more Nigeria-centered.</p>
  </div>

  <p>
    For this project, the payment experience should be built around <strong>one-time donations</strong>,
    <strong>monthly recurring donations</strong>, and <strong>cause-specific giving</strong>. This is the right
    structure for a humanitarian and community impact platform. A traditional SaaS-style billing model is not the
    right fit for the mission, audience, or funding flow.
  </p>

  <h2>3. What the Platform Actually Needs</h2>
  <h3>Core payment capabilities</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>One-time donations for supporters who want to contribute immediately.</li>
    <li>Recurring monthly donations for long-term supporters and sponsors.</li>
    <li>Cause-specific donations so donors can choose education, health, sports, arts, or a named project.</li>
    <li>Support for local African payment methods, especially Ghana mobile money.</li>
    <li>Support for international cards and globally familiar checkout options.</li>
    <li>Payment tagging and metadata for transparency, campaign reporting, and impact tracking.</li>
    <li>Webhook-based confirmation so donation status is verified securely on the server.</li>
    <li>Receipts or donation confirmations for donors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Why this is needed</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>The platform is raising support for humanitarian work, not selling access to a paid product.</li>
    <li>The donor audience includes both local African supporters and international supporters.</li>
    <li>Trust, transparency, and ease of payment are critical to fundraising performance.</li>
    <li>Donors should be able to give toward a mission area they care about, not just make a generic payment.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4. Recommended Gateway Strategy</h2>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Option</th>
      <th>Recommendation Level</th>
      <th>Why It Fits</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Flutterwave</td>
      <td>Best primary choice</td>
      <td>
        Strong fit for African fundraising use cases, supports Ghana card and Ghana mobile money,
        and works well for both local and international donors.
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Paystack</td>
      <td>Strong alternative</td>
      <td>
        Excellent if the main operating structure is Nigeria-led, with strong support for cards,
        mobile money, metadata, webhooks, and African payment operations.
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PayPal</td>
      <td>Secondary optional channel</td>
      <td>
        Useful for international donor familiarity and recurring giving, but not strong enough as the only
        payment method for this platform because it does not cover local African payment behavior well enough.
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>5. Recommended Setup for This Project</h2>
  <h3>Preferred setup</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary checkout:</strong> Flutterwave</li>
    <li><strong>Optional secondary checkout:</strong> PayPal</li>
    <li><strong>Payment structure:</strong> one-time and monthly donation flows</li>
    <li><strong>Donation routing:</strong> general donation plus cause-specific campaigns</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Why Flutterwave is the best first choice</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>It supports Ghana card payments and Ghana mobile money, which is highly relevant to the project context.</li>
    <li>It supports broader African and international payment options as the platform expands.</li>
    <li>It is more aligned with an Africa-first donor base than a PayPal-only setup.</li>
    <li>It gives a better foundation for future regional growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>When Paystack may be the better primary choice</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>If the organization is formally operating and settling mainly through Nigeria.</li>
    <li>If the team prefers Paystack's ecosystem, tooling, or compliance flow.</li>
    <li>If Nigerian payment rails and operational support are more central than Ghana-first expansion.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>6. What Should Not Be the Main Payment Model</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Do not use SaaS subscription billing as the main model.</strong> This platform is not charging users for software access.</li>
    <li><strong>Do not rely on PayPal only.</strong> That would weaken local donor conversion in Africa.</li>
    <li><strong>Do not start with a complex donor dashboard.</strong> It can come later after donation flows are working well.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>7. Phase 1 Payment Scope</h2>
  <p><strong>This is what should be built first:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Donate button in the main navigation and homepage hero.</li>
    <li>One-time donation form with preset and custom amounts.</li>
    <li>Monthly donation option.</li>
    <li>Campaign selection:
      Education, Health, Sports, Arts, General Support, or specific project pages.
    </li>
    <li>Support for local cards and mobile money.</li>
    <li>Support for international cards.</li>
    <li>Server-side payment verification.</li>
    <li>Donation success page and confirmation email.</li>
    <li>Basic admin reporting showing amount, date, donor details if provided, and campaign/category.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>8. Phase 2 Payment Scope</h2>
  <p><strong>These can come after launch:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>PayPal as an additional international giving option.</li>
    <li>Major donor and NGO sponsorship inquiry flow.</li>
    <li>Public transparency tracker fed by verified donations and project updates.</li>
    <li>Named campaigns with fundraising targets.</li>
    <li>Donor dashboard for returning supporters.</li>
    <li>Offline pledge capture and bank transfer reconciliation tools.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>9. Donation Types to Support</h2>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Donation Type</th>
      <th>Needed Now?</th>
      <th>Reason</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>One-time donation</td>
      <td>Yes</td>
      <td>Fastest and most common way for supporters to contribute.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Monthly recurring donation</td>
      <td>Yes</td>
      <td>Creates stable support for ongoing humanitarian work.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Cause-specific donation</td>
      <td>Yes</td>
      <td>Improves donor trust and gives people control over what they are funding.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Corporate sponsorship or institutional giving</td>
      <td>Yes, but via inquiry/contact first</td>
      <td>Large support will often need custom handling rather than self-serve checkout.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Membership fee or product subscription</td>
      <td>No</td>
      <td>Not aligned with the platform's mission and fundraising model.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>10. Technical Guidance</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Use server-side verification for every successful payment event.</li>
    <li>Store campaign identifiers in payment metadata so donations can be tied to education, health, sports, arts, or a project.</li>
    <li>Use webhook handlers to confirm completed payments rather than trusting frontend redirects alone.</li>
    <li>Design the donation records so reporting can show donation totals by campaign, date, geography, and payment channel.</li>
    <li>Make checkout mobile-first because many local donors will complete payments on phones.</li>
    <li>Keep the form lightweight and fast for low-bandwidth users.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>11. Transparency and Trust Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Because the platform is mission-driven and donor-facing, payment design should reinforce credibility.
    The payment system should support:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Clear cause labels on each donation.</li>
    <li>Donation confirmation and receipt delivery.</li>
    <li>Simple summaries of how donations support real programs.</li>
    <li>Optional progress indicators for campaigns and projects.</li>
    <li>Secure and familiar checkout language.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>12. Final Recommendation</h2>
  <div class="highlight">
    <p>
      For this humanitarian platform, the best payment approach is to build a <strong>donation-based payment system</strong>
      using <strong>Flutterwave as the primary gateway</strong>, with <strong>PayPal as an optional international donor channel</strong>
      and <strong>Paystack as a strong alternative if the operation is more Nigeria-centered</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The launch version should support <strong>one-time donations</strong>, <strong>monthly recurring donations</strong>,
      and <strong>cause-specific giving</strong> across education, health, sports, arts, and general support.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    This approach best matches the mission, the target audience, the geography, and the need for trust,
    accessibility, and long-term growth.
  </p>
</body>
</html>
